            <p>
                The U.S. Army Operating Concept, Win in a Complex World and the Army Warfighting
                Challenges (AWFC) describe how future Army forces operate to accomplish campaign
                objectives and protect United States national interests. Intelligence assessments
                and the Army family of concepts, along with strategy and planning documents, tell
                us that, within this environment, the IED will remain an enduring threat ─ “the
                single most effective countermeasure to U.S. Army advantages in armor protection,
                mobility, firepower and survivability…” (Army Counter Explosive Improvised Device
                Campaign Plan). General Martin Dempsey, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, further
                stated: “Improvised explosive devices remain the single most dangerous threat to
                our soldiers—all branches and all ranks—on the battlefield. They are very clearly
                an enduring threat.” The Army Capability Integration Center (ARCIC), in concert
                with the Training and Doctrine Command’s Centers of Excellence (CoE), is leading
                the effort to mitigate this threat and promote freedom of action, preservation of
                combat power and an enhanced security environment.
            </p>
            <h3>
                C-IEDs and Explosive Hazards
            </h3>
            <p>
                As the Army draws down in the wake of Operations Iraqi and Enduring Freedom, and
                coupled with an increasingly constrained fiscal environment, the Army faces difficult
                decisions. In this decision process, the Army must preserve C-IED lessons learned
                and enduring capabilities developed during 13 years of combat. ARCIC is fully engaged
                to ensure lessons learned and C-IED enduring capabilities become the baseline to
                posture Force 2025 and Beyond. ARCIC is also expanding its focus to the larger explosive
                hazard (EH) threat, of which IEDs are a sub-set. In the past, EHs were addressed
                primarily through rapid acquisition processes, resulting in a proliferation of non-standard
                equipment. However, what worked in the past cannot be sustained, especially in light
                of fiscal realities. With anticipated reductions in end strength, ARCIC is providing
                analysis and integration for prioritization of future and current needs and supporting
                trade-space decisions to reduce the force while developing Army combat capabilities
                for the future.
            </p>
            <div class="blockCallout" id="alignRt">
                <div class="blocktitle" id="Div2">
                    ----------</div>
                <div class="blockimage">
                    <asp:HyperLink ID="HyperLink2" runat="server" NavigateUrl="~/app_Inc-Popup/photo-fullsize.aspx?photo=20150622-01-01-0075-02"
                        CssClass="std" rel="facebox">
